/*
a [derivative of f(t)] == [instantaneous rate of change over of f(t) t]
[derivative of [absememt(t)]] == [[distance(t)]]
[derivative of [distance(t)]] == [[speed(t)]]
[derivative of [speed(t)]]    == [[acceleration]]

This CommonTab valculatesthe 3rd derivative of a v3 trough many functions:
data types that start with [d*] imply Automatic Differentiation
functions  that start with [D*] imply explicit typecasting to type [d*]

a. == first parameter, , ends up being OuterFunction,dividend
b. == second parameter , ends up being innerFunction,divisor
c. == third parameter  , ends up being interpolant
...
.a==0th derivative
.b==1th derivative
.c==2th derivative
.d==3th derivative
...
foreach derivative we use either type; v0, or v1 ,or v2 ,or v3
depending on how many dimensions the function/isoline/isosurface/isovolume has:
[d*  ]dt =+1th derivative
[d** ]dt²=+2th derivative (and dt)
[d***]dt³=+3th derivative (and dt adnd dt²)
[*N*] sets number of domains|dimensions to differentiate over (in parallel)
      these are commonly orthogonal domains of space.xyzw
(number of N) in [dN**] sets how many differentials we want to calculate
     a 1st derivative is rather simple to get
,but a 2nd derivative usually implies ProductRule or QuotientRule
,and a 3rd derivative has diminished utility with recursive complexity (productRules of productRules)
,and a 4th derivative is not even attempted (except for simple identities?)
